'''Flight mode''' is a function in some electronic devices (notably [[mobile phones]]) that deactivates [[radio transmitters]] and receivers such that the phone's secondary features (such as its music and [[java games|games]]) can be used in places such as [[passenger jet|planes]] and [[clinic|hospitals]].

Flight mode (or [[airplane mode]]) mostly applies to cell phones, but it also applicable to any electronic device that transmits radio signals as its primary function.
Despite the name, however, said function is not legally allowed on public flights as there is no clear indication whether or not a phone is actually transmitting data.  As a practical matter most cell phone users simply treat flight mode as a power-saving feature or a soft-off.

The [[Sony Ericsson W800]] mobile phone was first to introduce this feature on its [[Walkman]]-brand phone; since then other brands have followed suit.